Continuous age instead of median split plus full controls

Full controls with continuous age and age squared

Restricted to batch 1 participants only (N=47)

Restricted to batch 3 participants only (N=47)

HC2 heteroskedasticity-robust SE; identical point estimate to baseline
HC3 heteroskedasticity-robust SE; identical point estimate to baseline
Classical (homoskedastic) SE; identical to controls/none_classical
Standard errors clustered by batch; identical point estimate
Permutation test (1000 permutations); p=0.0 confirms strong result
Full controls with HC3 SE; combines control and inference variation
Logit model with average marginal effects (-0.252 vs OLS -0.256)
Probit model with average marginal effects (-0.248 vs OLS -0.256)
Logit with full controls; average marginal effect -0.224
Probit with full controls; average marginal effect -0.227
Median regression on share optimal shows zero effect because median is 1.0 in both groups; confirms extensive margin interpretation rather than testing same claim
25th percentile regression; different outcome (continuous share) and different estimand (conditional quantile)
Share optimal in initial allocation on Day 1 only; different outcome variable (continuous share vs binary across-all-days)
Share allocated to highest-return account (20%) Day 1; different outcome measuring allocation portfolio directly
Share allocated to Account 3 (15% rate / Debt 1) Day 1; different outcome with opposite expected sign (positive = more to lower-return account)
Weighted average return rate Day 1; different continuous outcome measuring efficiency loss in rate terms
Log weighted average return rate Day 1; log transform of alternative outcome
Binary optimal indicator pooled across days 1-4 (N=688); different outcome (single-day binary vs cumulative-all-days binary)
Optimal in all additional (not initial) allocations; different outcome variable measuring a different set of decisions
Number of accounts used Day 1; different outcome measuring diversification behavior (positive coef=more accounts used with debt)
No points allocated to Account 3/Debt 1 (cumulative); coefficient and SE identical to baseline -- appears to be same variable recoded or mechanically equivalent
Total share allocated to Account 1 across all days; different outcome aggregating continuous allocation over time
Optimal in one-shot no-debt scenario; placebo test -- should show no treatment effect when debt is absent (coef ~0 as expected)
Optimal in one-shot low-debt scenario; near-zero insignificant effect in one-shot version of the task
Share to Account 2 (10% return) Day 1; different outcome measuring allocation to second-best account
Herfindahl concentration index of allocation Day 1; different outcome measuring portfolio concentration
Log average return rate Day 1; duplicate of outcome/ln_avg_rate_day1 (same coefficient -0.099)
Log avg return rate with full controls Day 1; different outcome variable with controls added
Binary indicator for any allocation to highest-return account Day 1; different outcome measuring extensive margin of allocation to best account
High Debt vs No Debt; same outcome but different treatment arm comparison -- tests whether effect extends to high debt (marginally significant p=0.07)
High Debt vs Low Debt direct comparison; same outcome testing dose-response between debt levels (positive coef means High Debt does BETTER than Low Debt)
Any Debt (Low+High pooled) vs No Debt; same outcome with broader treatment definition
Continuous debt amount as treatment; tests linearity of dose-response (insignificant p=0.18 -- effect is not proportional to debt level)
Both debt dummies (Low and High) included; Low Debt coefficient identified with High Debt controlled for
Pooled OLS across days 1-4 with day fixed effects (N=688); same binary outcome per-day with day FE
Pooled OLS with day FE and demographic controls
Pooled with day FE and SEs clustered by individual (N=688)
Day 1 single-day optimal allocation; strongest effect (-0.279)
Day 2 single-day optimal allocation (-0.233)
Day 3 single-day optimal allocation; insignificant (-0.116 p=0.13)
Day 4 single-day optimal allocation; near zero (-0.012 p=0.88) showing convergence by end
Redistribution treatment experiment: different experimental condition from same study (-0.289 p<0.001)
Redistribution treatment with full controls; different experimental condition
Redistribution: consolidation behavior Day 1; different experimental condition and different outcome
Borrowing treatment: max borrowing from both accounts; different experimental condition and different outcome
Borrowing treatment with full controls + batch FE; different experimental condition
Borrowing: log cumulative returns with controls; different experimental condition and outcome

Balance test: gender by treatment assignment (p=0.538); confirms random assignment
Balance test: college education by treatment assignment (p=0.406); confirms random assignment
